title: Bryce Gibbs contract, trade to Adelaide, Carlton midfielder focused | Gold Coast Bulletin
text:
Bryce Gibbs says his focus is fixed squarely on footy, not his future Riley Beveridge, FOX SPORTS February 23, 2017 7:18pm 
CARLTON midfielder Bryce Gibbs says his focus is fixed squarely on the 2017 season, saying he would be “kidding himself” if he was already thinking about his future. 
Gibbs was one of the exchange period’s biggest stories last year after requesting a trade back to his home state of South Australia, despite having three years to run on his contract with Carlton. 
As a result, a deal with Adelaide failed to materialise throughout the trade period, with neither club able to negotiate suitable compensation. 
Gibbs subsequently returned to Ikon Park and is set to begin his 11th season with the Blues, refusing to speculate on whether the same situation will again unfold at the end of this year. 
“I’m not looking too far ahead,” Gibbs told SEN on Thursday. 
“I’d be kidding myself if I was thinking six to eight months down the track. 
“As soon as the decision was made that I was staying at Carlton, where I was more than happy to stay, my focus was purely on getting back into another pre-season. 
“I’m a leader at the footy club, I’ve played 200 games and I love the place, so that’s all my focus is on. 
“I’ve got through another pre-season, I’m feeling fit and I’m feeling good in myself. I’m just excited to attack another year at the club.” 
Gibbs enjoyed arguably a career-best year at Carlton in 2016, averaging 26.8 disposals through the midfield and registering 18 goals from 22 matches. 
But the 27-year-old believes he’s felt as good as ever throughout the club’s current pre-season program and says he’s looking forward to resuming action. 
“It’s completely fine,” Gibbs said. 
“There were a few things going on towards the end of last year and I seeked a trade back to Adelaide. That didn’t happen. (But) it wasn’t a football decision. 
“It’s been publicised why I seeked a trade. It had nothing to do with footy, which is why going back to the club was really smooth and really easy. 
“From day one of pre-season, it was back to business as usual and I’ve enjoyed pre-season — my 11th one at Carlton — more than I ever have.”
